WEBVTT

03:08.501 --> 03:10.336
Thank you very much

03:10.337 --> 03:11.671
and welcome to
<i>To Tell the Truth.</i>

03:11.672 --> 03:13.940
Our first guest,
he's made a career

03:13.974 --> 03:16.142
out of being the most
outrageous impostor

03:16.143 --> 03:18.211
that we've ever come
across on this show

03:18.212 --> 03:20.112
and you're going to
see what I mean.

03:20.113 --> 03:23.049
Number One,
what is your name, please?

03:23.050 --> 03:24.884
My name is
Frank William Abagnale.

03:24.885 --> 03:26.219
Number Two?

03:26.220 --> 03:28.554
My name is
Frank William Abagnale.

03:28.555 --> 03:29.889
Number Three?

03:29.890 --> 03:32.058
My name is
Frank William Abagnale.

03:32.059 --> 03:36.279
"From 1964 to 1967,
I successfully impersonated"

03:36.280 --> 03:38.948
"an airline pilot
for Pan Am Airways"

03:38.949 --> 03:42.218
"and I flew over
two million miles for free."

03:42.219 --> 03:45.888
"During that time, I was also
the chief resident pediatrician"

03:45.889 --> 03:47.823
"at a Georgia hospital"

03:47.824 --> 03:49.858
"and an assistant
attorney general"

03:49.859 --> 03:51.594
"for the State of Louisiana."

03:51.595 --> 03:53.963
"By the time I was caught,
I was considered"

03:53.964 --> 03:56.966
"the youngest and most daring
con man in U.S. history."

03:56.967 --> 04:00.403
"I had cashed almost $4 million
in fraudulent checks"

04:00.404 --> 04:03.772
"in 26 foreign countries
and all 50 states."

04:03.773 --> 04:07.143
"And I did it all
before my 19th birthday."

04:07.144 --> 04:10.246
"My name is
Frank William Abagnale."

04:10.247 --> 04:12.148
<i>♪ You don't know how ♪
♪ to tell the truth... ♪</i>

04:13.250 --> 04:14.902
<i>♪ You don't know how ♪
♪ to tell the truth... ♪</i>

04:14.903 --> 04:16.219
So, for the first time

04:16.220 --> 04:17.820
he's going to have
to tell the truth

04:17.821 --> 04:20.189
and we're going to start
our questioning with Kitty.

04:20.190 --> 04:22.742
Thank you. Number One,
why, with all your talent...

04:22.743 --> 04:24.912
and you're obviously
a very bright fellow...

04:24.913 --> 04:27.963
why didn't you go in
for a legitimate profession?

04:27.964 --> 04:30.500
It was really a question
of dollars and cents.

04:30.501 --> 04:32.136
When I was a young man,
I needed the money

04:32.137 --> 04:33.903
and I thought
this list of careers

04:33.904 --> 04:35.605
was the easiest way to get it.

04:35.606 --> 04:36.973
I see.

04:36.974 --> 04:39.409
Number Two, I find this all
very fascinating.

04:39.410 --> 04:41.345
Who was it
that finally caught you?

04:42.146 --> 04:44.413
His name was Carl Hanratty.

04:44.414 --> 04:46.449
Han-an-an-ratty.

04:46.450 --> 04:47.650
Ratty.

04:47.651 --> 04:49.084
Hanratty.

04:49.085 --> 04:50.119
Han-ratty.

04:50.120 --> 04:52.421
Carl Hanratty.

04:52.422 --> 04:53.789
Yes. I...

04:53.790 --> 04:56.392
am... Carl Hanratty.

04:56.393 --> 05:00.796
I represent the FBI from
the United States of America.

05:02.432 --> 05:04.233
Yeah. I have orders

05:04.234 --> 05:07.170
to see the American
prisoner, Abagnale.

05:33.997 --> 05:37.500
You sit here.

05:37.501 --> 05:40.336
You do not open the door.

05:40.337 --> 05:44.006
You do not pass him...

05:44.007 --> 05:47.376
anything through the hole.

05:57.020 --> 05:59.021
Aw... Jesus.

06:19.409 --> 06:21.644
You know, I've got
a little bit of a cold myself.

06:21.645 --> 06:22.911
Frank...

06:22.912 --> 06:25.581
I'm here to read
the articles of extradition

06:25.582 --> 06:28.150
according to the
European Court for Human Rights.

06:28.151 --> 06:30.786
"Article One,
Extradition shall be granted"

06:30.787 --> 06:33.021
"in respect of offenses
punishable under the laws..."

06:33.022 --> 06:34.390
Help me.

06:34.391 --> 06:36.592
"...for the maximum period
of at least one year"

06:36.593 --> 06:38.894
"of a severe penalty."

06:38.895 --> 06:40.062
Help me.

06:40.063 --> 06:43.198
Frank... stop it.

06:43.199 --> 06:45.501
Help me.

06:45.502 --> 06:48.170
You don't think actually
you can fool me, do you?

06:50.173 --> 06:52.475
16 pages to go.
Stay with me.

06:52.476 --> 06:54.710
"Article Two."

06:54.711 --> 06:56.279
"If the request for extradition"

06:56.280 --> 06:58.013
"includes several separate
offenses"

06:58.014 --> 06:59.448
"each of which is punishable
under the laws..."

07:00.450 --> 07:01.784
"of the requesting party..."

07:01.785 --> 07:03.986
Frank?

07:05.889 --> 07:08.056
Frank?

07:08.057 --> 07:09.158
Goddamn it!

07:09.159 --> 07:12.060
Get me a doctor in here!

07:12.061 --> 07:13.562
Yes.
I need a doctor!

07:13.563 --> 07:14.930
Doctor! Now!

07:14.931 --> 07:16.432
Don't sweat it, Frank.

07:16.433 --> 07:18.401
We're going to get you
right to a doctor.

07:21.672 --> 07:23.572
Frank, if you can
hear me, don't worry.

07:23.573 --> 07:25.608
I'm going to take you
home in the morning.

07:25.609 --> 07:26.942
Home in the morning, Frank.

07:31.281 --> 07:32.615
What are you doing?

07:32.616 --> 07:33.949
Washing off the lice.

07:33.950 --> 07:36.385
This man has to be on a plane
for America.

07:36.386 --> 07:37.787
He has to see a doctor.

07:37.788 --> 07:39.488
The doctor comes in tomorrow.

07:39.489 --> 07:41.457
I have worked too long,
too hard

07:41.458 --> 07:43.592
for you to take
this away from me.

07:43.593 --> 07:46.128
If he dies, I'm holding
you responsible.

07:52.268 --> 07:53.903
Monsieur!

07:58.107 --> 07:59.908
Ah, Frank.

08:42.118 --> 08:43.885
Okay, Carl...

08:43.886 --> 08:46.989
let's go home.

08:46.990 --> 08:49.592
<i>The New Rochelle Rotary Club</i>

08:49.593 --> 08:52.628
<i>has a history</i>
<i>that goes back to 1919.</i>

08:52.629 --> 08:54.096
In all those years

08:54.097 --> 08:57.966
we've only seen a handful
of deserving gentlemen

08:57.967 --> 09:00.836
inducted as lifetime members.

09:00.837 --> 09:02.872
It's an honor that, uh

09:02.873 --> 09:07.676
that has seen 57 names enshrined
on the wall of honor

09:07.677 --> 09:10.212
and tonight, we make it 58.

09:10.213 --> 09:13.682
So please stand as I present
my very good friend

09:13.683 --> 09:16.318
a man who keeps
our pencils sharp...

09:17.821 --> 09:19.555
and our pens in ink...

09:19.556 --> 09:22.224
Frank William Abagnale.

09:42.111 --> 09:43.712
I stand here humbled

09:43.713 --> 09:46.916
by the presence
of Mayor Robert Wagner...

09:51.354 --> 09:54.423
and our club president,
Jack Barnes.

09:59.429 --> 10:03.265
Most of all, I'm honored to see
my loving wife Paula...

10:05.836 --> 10:09.371
and my son, Frank Jr...

10:09.372 --> 10:11.540
Frank... Aw, stand up.
Come on...

10:15.011 --> 10:17.513
...sitting in the front row.

10:22.285 --> 10:27.089
Two little mice fell
in a bucket of cream.

10:27.090 --> 10:31.994
The first mouse quickly gave up
and drowned.

10:31.995 --> 10:36.365
The second mouse...
wouldn't quit.

10:36.366 --> 10:37.867
He struggled so hard

10:37.868 --> 10:41.504
that eventually he churned
that cream into butter

10:41.505 --> 10:43.405
and crawled out.

10:43.406 --> 10:47.710
Gentlemen, as of this moment,
I am that second mouse.

11:04.861 --> 11:07.563
You're a better dancer
than your father, Frankie.

11:07.564 --> 11:09.164
You hear that, Daddy?

11:09.165 --> 11:10.365
Like fun.

11:10.366 --> 11:12.367
The girls don't
know what they're in for.

11:12.368 --> 11:15.404
Show him the dance
you were doing when we met.

11:15.405 --> 11:16.839
Ah, who can remember?

11:16.840 --> 11:19.374
The people
in that little French village

11:19.375 --> 11:21.276
were so happy to see Americans

11:21.277 --> 11:23.646
they decided
to put on a show for us.

11:23.647 --> 11:25.648
So they crammed 200 soldiers...

11:25.649 --> 11:27.650
Yeah, we know the story, Daddy.

11:27.651 --> 11:29.552
Into that tiny social hall

11:29.553 --> 11:31.887
and the first person
to walk onstage

11:31.888 --> 11:34.523
is your mother, and
she starts to dance.

11:34.524 --> 11:35.858
You know

11:35.859 --> 11:39.695
it had been months
since we'd even seen a woman

11:39.696 --> 11:41.563
and here's this blonde angel.

11:41.564 --> 11:43.031
Blonde bombshell.

11:44.868 --> 11:48.203
And the men are literally
holding their breath.

11:48.204 --> 11:49.772
Holding their breath for you.

11:49.773 --> 11:50.906
You hear that?

11:51.908 --> 11:52.908
Mm-hmm.

11:52.909 --> 11:55.143
And I turned to my buddies
and I said...

11:55.144 --> 11:57.312
"I will not leave
France without her."

11:57.313 --> 11:58.647
And I didn't.

11:58.648 --> 12:00.282
You didn't.

12:00.283 --> 12:02.150
I didn't.

12:03.185 --> 12:05.387
Oh, shit!
Oh, shit, the rug!

12:05.388 --> 12:06.388
Aw, Mom...

12:06.389 --> 12:07.523
I can't believe I did that.

12:07.524 --> 12:09.024
No, no, it's nothing.
It's nothing.

12:09.025 --> 12:10.559
Oh, Frankie, Frankie,
get a towel.

12:10.560 --> 12:11.560
Paula...
Yeah, yeah.

12:11.561 --> 12:12.561
Come on.

12:12.562 --> 12:16.398
<i>♪ My sweet embraceable you... ♪</i>

12:16.399 --> 12:18.600
Dance with me, Paula.

12:20.503 --> 12:23.338
Ah...

12:29.211 --> 12:31.046
Whenever I dance for you

12:31.047 --> 12:33.148
I get in trouble.

12:39.288 --> 12:41.089
Watch this.

12:43.326 --> 12:46.294
Oh!

12:46.295 --> 12:47.295
Frank! Wake up.

12:47.296 --> 12:48.864
Come on, let's go!

12:48.865 --> 12:50.933
Get up.
Come on, come on.

12:50.934 --> 12:52.133
Frank, wake up.

12:52.134 --> 12:53.368
Dad...

12:53.369 --> 12:55.236
You don't have to go
to school today.

12:55.237 --> 12:56.672
It's okay.

12:56.673 --> 12:58.206
Why? Is it snowing?

12:58.207 --> 12:59.675
Do you have a black suit?

12:59.676 --> 13:01.510
I overslept again, huh?

13:01.511 --> 13:05.080
We have a very important
meeting in the city.

13:05.081 --> 13:06.982
Eat that.
Come on, come on, eat.

13:06.983 --> 13:08.617
Ma'am, open up.
Just open up, please!

13:08.618 --> 13:09.618
Ma'am?
It's important.

13:09.619 --> 13:10.786
What?

13:10.787 --> 13:12.387
Oh, gosh!

13:12.388 --> 13:13.722
We don't open for half an hour!

13:13.723 --> 13:15.591
Open the door, please.
Just open the door.

13:15.592 --> 13:16.592
It's important.

13:16.593 --> 13:18.560
I-I'm sorry, we don't open
for half an hour.

13:18.561 --> 13:19.661
What's your name, ma'am?

13:19.662 --> 13:20.863
Darcy.

13:20.864 --> 13:21.997
Darcy.
That's a pretty name.

13:21.998 --> 13:23.765
I'm in a bit of a fix.
I need a suit for my kid.

13:23.766 --> 13:24.766
This is my son Frank.

13:24.767 --> 13:25.767
Oh, hi.

13:25.768 --> 13:26.768
He needs a black suit.

13:26.769 --> 13:28.169
Black suit...

13:28.170 --> 13:29.538
There was a death
in the family.

13:29.539 --> 13:31.039
My father, 85 years old,
war hero.

13:31.040 --> 13:33.041
Yeah?

13:33.042 --> 13:35.844
There's a funeral
this afternoon, military funeral

13:35.845 --> 13:38.013
planes flying overhead,
21-gun salute.

13:38.014 --> 13:39.347
Geez.

13:39.348 --> 13:41.316
Frank needs to borrow a suit

13:41.317 --> 13:42.518
for a couple of hours.

13:42.519 --> 13:45.453
I'm sorry, we don't loan suits,
and we're not open.

13:45.454 --> 13:46.822
Darcy... Darcy, please.

13:46.823 --> 13:48.724
Come back.

13:48.725 --> 13:50.859
Darcy... is this yours?

13:56.533 --> 13:59.267
I just found it
in the parking lot.

13:59.268 --> 14:01.436
Uh-huh.

14:01.437 --> 14:04.005
It must've slipped
right off your neck.

14:06.643 --> 14:08.844
Don't hit the curb.

14:13.650 --> 14:15.551
Now get out,
walk around the back

14:15.552 --> 14:17.485
and hold the door open for me.

14:26.796 --> 14:28.063
All right.

14:28.064 --> 14:29.297
What's next?

14:29.298 --> 14:30.699
Okay, stop grinning.

14:30.700 --> 14:34.135
When I get inside, you go back
to the front seat and wait.

14:34.136 --> 14:36.672
Even if a cop comes
and writes you a ticket

14:36.673 --> 14:38.740
you don't move the car,
understood?

14:38.741 --> 14:40.676
Dad, wha-what's
all this for?

14:40.677 --> 14:42.778
You know why the Yankees
always win, Frank?

14:42.779 --> 14:44.446
'Cause they have Mickey Mantle?

14:44.447 --> 14:46.147
No, it's 'cause the other teams

14:46.148 --> 14:48.617
can't stop staring
at those damn pinstripes.

14:48.618 --> 14:49.651
Watch this.

14:49.652 --> 14:51.553
The manager
of Chase Manhattan Bank

14:51.554 --> 14:56.158
is about to open the
door for your father.

14:57.627 --> 15:00.062
Mr. Abagnale, um

15:00.063 --> 15:02.163
we don't usually
loan money to people

15:02.164 --> 15:04.566
who have unresolved business
with the IRS.

15:04.567 --> 15:06.434
That's a misunderstanding.

15:06.435 --> 15:08.203
I hired the wrong
guy to do my books.

15:08.204 --> 15:10.005
A mistake, I...
anybody could make it.

15:10.006 --> 15:12.373
I just need you guys to
help me weather the storm.

15:12.374 --> 15:14.710
Sir, you're being investigated
by the government

15:14.711 --> 15:16.712
for tax fraud.

15:16.713 --> 15:18.847
My store is a landmark
in New Rochelle.

15:18.848 --> 15:20.782
I have customers
all over New York.

15:20.783 --> 15:23.418
Well, you're not a customer
at Chase Manhattan.

15:23.419 --> 15:24.519
We don't know you.

15:24.520 --> 15:26.321
I'm sure your bank
in New Rochelle

15:26.322 --> 15:28.423
they know you,
they could help you out.

15:28.424 --> 15:29.992
My bank went out of business.

15:29.993 --> 15:32.427
Banks like this one put
them out of business.

15:32.428 --> 15:34.596
Now, I know I made a
mistake, I admit that

15:34.597 --> 15:36.098
but these people want blood.

15:36.099 --> 15:37.099
They want my store.

15:37.100 --> 15:39.034
They've threatened
to put me in jail.

15:40.670 --> 15:42.237
This is America, right?

15:42.238 --> 15:43.304
I'm not a criminal.

15:43.305 --> 15:44.840
I'm a Medal of Honor winner

15:44.841 --> 15:47.643
a lifetime member
of the New Rochelle Rotary Club.

15:47.644 --> 15:50.612
All I'm asking is for you
to help me beat these guys.

15:50.613 --> 15:53.181
It's not a question
of winning and losing.

15:53.182 --> 15:54.716
It's a question of risk.

15:54.717 --> 15:57.418
You're the largest
bank in the world.

15:57.419 --> 15:59.054
Where's the fu...

15:59.055 --> 16:01.957
Whe... Where's the risk?

16:06.929 --> 16:09.931
Dad, how could you just let him
take our car like that?

16:09.932 --> 16:11.967
He didn't take anything.
We took him.

16:11.968 --> 16:13.135
He overpaid by $500.

16:13.136 --> 16:16.404
Come on, Frank.

16:16.405 --> 16:17.873
Let's return the suit.

16:25.715 --> 16:27.215
This place is good.

16:27.216 --> 16:29.184
It's small but, you know

16:29.185 --> 16:31.753
it's going to be
a lot less work.

16:31.754 --> 16:33.354
A lot less work for you.

16:56.478 --> 16:57.813
Hey, Dad.

16:57.814 --> 17:00.015
Hi.

17:03.385 --> 17:05.453
Where's your mother?

17:05.454 --> 17:06.621
I don't know.

17:06.622 --> 17:11.259
She said something
about going to look for a job.

17:12.394 --> 17:13.560
What's she gonna be

17:13.561 --> 17:15.496
a shoe salesman
at a centipede farm?

17:21.604 --> 17:23.137
What are you doing?

17:24.673 --> 17:26.974
You want some pancakes?

17:26.976 --> 17:27.976
For dinner?

17:27.977 --> 17:29.878
On my son's 16th birthday?

17:29.879 --> 17:32.213
We're not gonna eat pancakes.

17:34.583 --> 17:37.219
Come on, why are you
looking at me like that?

17:37.220 --> 17:38.486
You thought I forgot?

17:38.487 --> 17:41.522
I didn't think you forgot.
I opened a checking account

17:41.523 --> 17:43.358
in your name.

17:43.359 --> 17:44.726
I put $25 in the account

17:44.727 --> 17:46.561
so you can buy
whatever you want.

17:46.562 --> 17:47.896
Don't tell your mother.

17:47.897 --> 17:48.997
I won't.

17:48.998 --> 17:50.198
Thanks, Dad.

17:50.199 --> 17:51.233
Yep.

17:51.234 --> 17:54.569
Didn't that bank turn you down
for a loan, though?

17:54.570 --> 17:56.004
Yes, they all turned me down.

17:57.406 --> 17:59.674
Then why you opening a
banking account with them?

17:59.675 --> 18:01.977
Well, because one day,
you'll want something

18:01.978 --> 18:03.879
from these people...
a house, a car.

18:03.880 --> 18:07.082
They have all the money.

18:09.652 --> 18:12.553
There's 50 checks there, Frank

18:12.554 --> 18:17.192
which means, from
this day on...

18:17.193 --> 18:19.394
you're in their little club.

18:19.395 --> 18:22.864
I'm in their little club.

18:22.865 --> 18:25.000
You got that, you got it all.

18:25.001 --> 18:29.404
It's even got
my name there, huh?

18:29.405 --> 18:30.738
To the moon.

18:30.739 --> 18:32.774
To the moon!

18:32.775 --> 18:35.743
To the moon.

18:44.053 --> 18:46.955
See that?
It's just a school.

18:46.956 --> 18:48.723
No different than Westbourne.

18:48.724 --> 18:52.727
Ma... you said you were
going to quit.

18:55.698 --> 18:59.234
Frankie, you don't have
to wear the uniform here.

18:59.235 --> 19:02.204
Why don't you take
off your jacket?

19:02.205 --> 19:05.240
I'm used to it.

19:09.611 --> 19:10.745
Excuse me.

19:10.746 --> 19:11.746
Oh, yes?

19:11.747 --> 19:13.648
Do you know where
room 17 French is?

19:13.649 --> 19:15.416
Yeah, it's...

19:23.659 --> 19:25.593
But you frickin' killed him.

19:29.131 --> 19:31.266
You selling encyclopedias?

19:31.267 --> 19:34.936
Yeah, he looks like
a substitute teacher.

19:49.551 --> 19:51.719
Quiet down, people!

19:51.720 --> 19:54.022
My name is Mr. Abagnale!

19:54.023 --> 19:57.259
That's Abagnale, not Abagnahlee

19:57.260 --> 20:00.695
not Abagnaylee, but Abagnale!

20:00.696 --> 20:02.931
Now, somebody please
tell me where you left off

20:02.932 --> 20:05.133
in your textbooks.

20:06.402 --> 20:08.136
Excuse me, people,
if I need to ask again

20:08.137 --> 20:09.804
I'm going to write up
the entire class.

20:09.805 --> 20:12.340
Take your seats!

20:16.312 --> 20:17.912
Chapter seven.

20:17.913 --> 20:20.348
Will you please open your
textbooks to, uh, chapter eight

20:20.349 --> 20:22.984
and we'll get started?

20:22.985 --> 20:24.486
Excuse me, what's your name?

20:24.487 --> 20:25.520
Brad.

20:25.521 --> 20:27.089
Brad, why don't you get up here

20:27.090 --> 20:28.957
in front of the class here

20:28.958 --> 20:32.327
and read conversation
number five?

20:34.863 --> 20:37.665
<i>"Les Francais sonts"</i>

20:37.666 --> 20:39.667
<i>"uh, generalement"</i>

20:39.668 --> 20:42.504
<i>"dans leur pais que..."</i>

20:42.505 --> 20:45.407
<i>"presque tout le monde</i>
<i>a cette impression..."</i>

20:45.408 --> 20:46.808
They sent for me.

20:46.809 --> 20:50.044
They said they needed
a sub for Roberta.

20:50.045 --> 20:52.880
I came all the way
from-from Dixon.

20:52.881 --> 20:55.683
Well, uh,
I always sub for Roberta.

20:56.084 --> 20:58.219
Excuse me,
why aren't you reading?

20:59.454 --> 21:02.689
I'll never come back to-to
Bellarmine Jefferson again!

21:02.690 --> 21:05.291
You tell them not to call me!

21:05.292 --> 21:07.728
What do they think,
it's easy for a woman my age

21:07.729 --> 21:09.863
and all the money that it costs
to travel?

21:09.864 --> 21:11.465
I tell you, they don't give a damn.

21:11.534 --> 21:13.001
Mr. and Mrs. Abagnale

21:13.002 --> 21:16.304
this is not a question
of your son's attendance.

21:16.305 --> 21:19.474
I regret to inform you that,
for the past week

21:19.475 --> 21:23.277
Frank has been teaching
Mrs. Glasser's French class.

21:24.447 --> 21:25.747
He what?

21:25.748 --> 21:29.884
Your son has been pretending
to be a substitute teacher

21:29.885 --> 21:34.256
lecturing the students,
uh, giving out homework.

21:34.257 --> 21:37.792
Mrs. Glasser has
been ill and there was

21:37.793 --> 21:40.795
some confusion
with the real sub.

21:40.796 --> 21:44.332
Your son held a teacher-parent
conference yesterday

21:44.333 --> 21:46.768
and was planning
a class field trip

21:46.769 --> 21:49.337
to a French bread factory
in Trenton.

21:49.338 --> 21:52.940
Do you see the problem we have?

21:52.941 --> 21:54.942
Yeah.
Mrs. Davenport?

21:54.943 --> 21:57.445
Uh, I have a note to miss
fifth and sixth period today.

21:57.446 --> 21:58.480
Doctor's appointment.

21:58.481 --> 22:00.615
One moment.

22:00.616 --> 22:01.916
I'll be right with you.

22:01.917 --> 22:02.917
Hey...

22:02.918 --> 22:03.918
Yes?

22:03.919 --> 22:05.153
You should fold it.

22:05.154 --> 22:06.254
What?

22:06.255 --> 22:07.922
That note.
It's a fake, right?

22:07.923 --> 22:09.257
You should fold it.

22:09.258 --> 22:11.059
It's... It's a note
from my mom.

22:11.060 --> 22:12.794
I have a doctor's appointment.

22:12.795 --> 22:15.697
Yeah, but there's
no crease in the paper.

22:15.698 --> 22:17.765
When your mom hands
you a note to miss school

22:17.766 --> 22:19.534
the first thing you do is,
you fold it

22:19.535 --> 22:20.935
and you put it in your pocket.

22:20.936 --> 22:24.305
I mean, if it's real,
where's the crease?

22:33.849 --> 22:35.383
Frankie.

22:50.766 --> 22:52.767
Ma, I'm home.

22:54.837 --> 22:56.838
Oh, you remember
that girl Joanna

22:56.839 --> 22:59.040
I was telling you about?

22:59.041 --> 23:01.176
I asked her out today.

23:02.177 --> 23:04.546
Think we're going to go
to the Junior Prom.

23:06.200 --> 23:08.416
Ma, is this
my driver's license?

23:08.417 --> 23:10.218
That's all there is,
two bedrooms.

23:10.819 --> 23:12.621
Oh, Frankie.

23:12.622 --> 23:14.589
You remember Dad's friend?

23:14.590 --> 23:16.524
Jack Barnes?

23:16.525 --> 23:17.825
From the club.

23:17.826 --> 23:18.860
Hello.

23:18.861 --> 23:20.828
He came by looking
for your father.

23:20.829 --> 23:23.598
I was giving him
a tour of the apartment.

23:23.599 --> 23:26.835
It's very, uh, uh,
spacious, Paula.

23:32.174 --> 23:34.476
Dad's at the store.

23:34.477 --> 23:37.512
So, Frank... you're
getting to look

23:37.513 --> 23:40.582
more like your
old man every day.

23:43.018 --> 23:45.453
Thanks for the sandwich, Paula.

23:45.454 --> 23:47.255
I'll see you later, eh?

23:47.256 --> 23:49.457
Wait.

23:53.396 --> 23:55.563
Is this yours?

23:55.564 --> 23:58.300
Oh.

23:58.301 --> 24:00.001
Well, thanks, Frank.

24:00.002 --> 24:02.370
Uh, that's the President's pin.

24:02.371 --> 24:05.006
I'd be in deep trouble
if I lost that.

24:10.879 --> 24:13.180
I'll see you all later, eh?

24:22.525 --> 24:24.693
Are you hungry, Frankie?

24:24.694 --> 24:27.294
I'll make you a sandwich.

24:35.237 --> 24:38.272
Jack wanted to talk business
with your father.

24:38.273 --> 24:40.408
He thinks we should
get a lawyer

24:40.409 --> 24:42.577
and sue the government.

24:43.912 --> 24:47.048
That is not legal,
what they're doing to us.

24:49.985 --> 24:52.186
Why aren't you saying anything?

24:58.394 --> 25:03.064
You're not going
to tell him... are you?

25:03.065 --> 25:04.833
No.

25:04.834 --> 25:06.133
That's right.

25:06.134 --> 25:08.870
There's nothing to tell.

25:08.871 --> 25:10.538
I'm going out for a few hours

25:10.539 --> 25:13.708
to visit some old friends
from the tennis club and...

25:13.709 --> 25:17.345
when I get home, we'll all
have dinner together.

25:17.346 --> 25:19.347
Right?

25:19.348 --> 25:21.416
But you won't say anything

25:21.417 --> 25:24.853
because it's...
it's just silly, isn't it?

25:24.854 --> 25:27.055
How could we sue anybody?

25:30.826 --> 25:35.296
Oh... do you need
some money, Frankie?

25:35.297 --> 25:39.133
A few dollars to buy
some record albums?

25:39.134 --> 25:42.303
Here, take five dollars.

25:42.304 --> 25:44.505
Or-Or ten.

25:49.845 --> 25:51.846
You promised you
were going to quit.

26:11.333 --> 26:13.534
Ma, I'm home!

26:28.216 --> 26:29.784
Hey, hey!

26:29.785 --> 26:31.152
You... You stay away from me,
hear me?

26:31.153 --> 26:32.921
You stay away from me...
I don't know who you are

26:32.922 --> 26:34.188
but if you ever
come back here again...

26:34.189 --> 26:36.458
Frankie! Frank, Frank,
calm down, will you?

26:36.459 --> 26:37.725
I'm Dick Kesner.

26:37.726 --> 26:39.928
Now, I want you
to leave your things here

26:39.929 --> 26:41.996
and follow me
into the next room, okay?

26:41.997 --> 26:43.765
They're all waiting for you.

26:46.635 --> 26:48.870
You don't have to be scared.

26:48.871 --> 26:50.905
I'm right here, Frank.
I'll always be here.

26:50.906 --> 26:52.640
But there are laws.

26:52.641 --> 26:54.876
Everything in this
country has to be legal.

26:54.877 --> 26:57.912
So what we need to do
is make some decisions.

26:57.913 --> 26:59.581
That's what Mr. Kesner
is here for.

26:59.582 --> 27:01.950
Many times these decisions
are left up to the courts

27:01.951 --> 27:03.417
but that can be
very expensive, Frank

27:03.418 --> 27:05.086
people fighting
over their children.

27:05.087 --> 27:06.788
Nobody is fighting.

27:06.789 --> 27:09.457
Look at me, Frank.
Nobody is fighting.

27:11.827 --> 27:14.128
Dad, what's going on?

27:14.129 --> 27:15.697
Dad, what's going on?

27:18.300 --> 27:19.967
Do you remember
your grandma, Eve?

27:19.968 --> 27:21.703
She arrived this morning.

27:23.138 --> 27:24.872
Hello.

27:33.014 --> 27:36.417
Do you understand what
we're saying to you, Frank?

27:37.853 --> 27:41.856
Your father and I
are getting a divorce.

27:44.393 --> 27:45.626
Nothing's gonna change.

27:45.627 --> 27:47.362
We're still gonna
see each other.

27:47.363 --> 27:49.296
Stop it, please, Frank.
Don't interrupt.

27:49.297 --> 27:51.666
Frank, you don't
have to read all of this.

27:51.667 --> 27:54.836
Most of it's for your parents...
boring adult business...

27:54.837 --> 27:57.605
but this paragraph right here,
this is important

27:57.606 --> 28:00.307
because it states
who you're gonna live with...

28:00.308 --> 28:02.309
after the divorce...

28:02.310 --> 28:04.278
whose custody you will be in.

28:04.279 --> 28:07.448
And there's a blank space
right here.

28:08.450 --> 28:09.917
And I want you to go
into the kitchen

28:09.918 --> 28:11.519
sit at the table

28:11.520 --> 28:13.220
and put a name down.

28:13.221 --> 28:14.555
You can take
as long as you want

28:14.556 --> 28:16.257
but when you come back
into this room...

28:16.258 --> 28:18.893
<i>I want to see a name</i>
<i>on that line.</i>

28:18.894 --> 28:22.663
Frank, just write down a name
and this will all be over.

28:22.664 --> 28:24.565
It's gonna be okay.

28:24.566 --> 28:26.367
<i>Dad, what name?</i>

28:26.368 --> 28:27.535
Your mother or your father.

28:27.536 --> 28:29.737
Just put the name there.
It's as simple as that.

28:29.738 --> 28:32.774
And don't look so scared.

28:32.775 --> 28:34.542
It's not a test.

28:34.543 --> 28:36.744
<i>There's no wrong answer.</i>

28:49.391 --> 28:50.391
Hi.

28:51.527 --> 28:53.093
One ticket to Grand
Central, please.

28:53.094 --> 28:56.363
That'll be $3.50, sir.

28:56.364 --> 28:59.399
Is it okay
if I write you a check?

29:04.239 --> 29:07.107
Carl, when do I get
to call my father?

29:07.108 --> 29:09.677
You can call him when
we get to New York.

29:09.678 --> 29:12.980
We leave for the airport
in seven hours.

29:12.981 --> 29:15.249
Until then, just sit there.

29:15.250 --> 29:18.018
Be quiet.

29:18.019 --> 29:20.387
You know, Carl,
on the other side of the hotel

29:20.388 --> 29:22.422
they got suites
that face the park.

29:23.358 --> 29:26.694
It's the best room
the FBI can afford.

29:28.864 --> 29:30.965
It's okay, I've stayed in worse.

29:30.966 --> 29:32.333
<i>Mr. Mudrick...</i>

29:32.334 --> 29:33.668
Mr. Mudrick, please.
You have to listen.

29:33.669 --> 29:35.470
I don't want to
hear your story.

29:35.471 --> 29:37.204
This is two checks
that bounced.

29:37.205 --> 29:39.039
You know how much
trouble I'm in?

29:39.040 --> 29:40.641
No, but listen, I'm telling you

29:40.642 --> 29:41.976
the bank,
they made the mistake.

29:41.977 --> 29:43.511
I'll write you
another check right now!

29:43.512 --> 29:45.480
What, do I look like
I was born yesterday?

29:45.481 --> 29:47.348
Look, it's midnight,
Mr. Mudrick.

29:47.349 --> 29:48.349
Where am I gonna go?

29:48.350 --> 29:49.984
You're a goddamn kid.

29:49.985 --> 29:52.186
Go home.

30:39.618 --> 30:40.918
I mean, I hope you understand.

30:40.919 --> 30:42.753
My boss sent me to Brooklyn,
then Queens.

30:42.754 --> 30:44.188
Now he wants me in Long Island

30:44.189 --> 30:46.691
to take a few clients out
for a night on the town.

30:46.692 --> 30:48.492
I'm sorry,
but we're not allowed

30:48.493 --> 30:50.294
to cash checks
from other banks.

30:50.295 --> 30:52.563
How would we know
if they were any good?

30:52.564 --> 30:54.298
What did you say your name was?

30:54.299 --> 30:55.299
Ashley.

30:55.300 --> 30:56.600
Ashley...

30:56.601 --> 30:58.802
you know what I found on
the sidewalk out there?

31:04.075 --> 31:06.443
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

31:10.716 --> 31:14.418
Is there something
I can help you with, son?

31:14.419 --> 31:16.854
Well, you see, it's my
grandmother's birthday next week

31:16.855 --> 31:18.889
and I want to get her
something extra-special.

31:18.890 --> 31:20.591
<i>Please, I mean</i>

31:20.592 --> 31:23.060
it's my midterm next week
and my books were stolen.

31:24.162 --> 31:26.096
Please, it's just five dollars.

31:26.097 --> 31:27.732
No one would have to know.

31:27.733 --> 31:30.368
I'm sorry,
but we are not allowed

31:30.369 --> 31:33.904
to take checks
from people we don't know.

32:15.447 --> 32:17.347
Pleasure to have you back,
Captain Carlson.

32:17.348 --> 32:18.783
What do you think, Angelo?

32:18.784 --> 32:20.418
The tomatoes are ripe
this afternoon.

32:28.359 --> 32:29.527
Well, what have we here?

32:29.528 --> 32:31.562
- Can I have your autograph?
- You betcha.

32:31.563 --> 32:33.597
- Can I have your autograph, too?
- You gonna be a pilot?

32:33.598 --> 32:35.766
- Mm-hmm!
- All right, then.

32:35.767 --> 32:37.301
There you go.
Work hard in school.

32:37.302 --> 32:38.669
<i>Dear Dad,</i>

32:38.670 --> 32:41.271
<i>I have decided to become</i>
<i>an airline pilot.</i>

32:41.272 --> 32:43.641
<i>I have applied</i>
<i>to all the big airlines</i>

32:43.642 --> 32:46.744
<i>and I have several</i>
<i>promising interviews lined up.</i>

32:46.745 --> 32:48.512
<i>How's Mom?</i>

32:48.513 --> 32:50.514
<i>Have you called her lately?</i>

32:50.515 --> 32:52.783
<i>Love, your son, Frank.</i>

32:55.954 --> 32:57.788
Hello.

32:57.789 --> 33:00.157
I'm Frank Black
from Murrow High School

33:00.158 --> 33:02.760
and I have an appointment
with Mr. Morgan.

33:02.761 --> 33:04.061
You're the young man

33:04.062 --> 33:05.996
who's writing the article
for the school paper.

33:05.997 --> 33:07.498
Yes, ma'am, that's me.
I want to know

33:07.499 --> 33:09.500
everything there is to know
about being a pilot.

33:09.501 --> 33:11.201
What airports
does Pan Am fly to?

33:11.202 --> 33:12.903
What does a pilot
make in a year?

33:12.904 --> 33:15.272
And who tells them where
they're gonna fly to?

33:15.273 --> 33:16.474
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Slow down.

33:16.475 --> 33:17.708
Just take 'em one at a time.

33:17.709 --> 33:18.876
All right.
What does it mean

33:18.877 --> 33:20.478
when one pilot says
to another pilot,

33:20.479 --> 33:22.045
"What kind of equipment
are you on?"

33:22.046 --> 33:24.582
They just want to know what
kind of aircraft you're flying,

33:24.583 --> 33:26.016
Is it a DC-8, 707,
Constellation?

33:26.017 --> 33:28.686
And what about those I.D. badges
that I've seen pilots wear?

33:28.687 --> 33:31.489
Well, every pilot has to have two
things with him at all times,

33:31.490 --> 33:33.123
One is his airline
personnel badge...

33:33.124 --> 33:35.125
looks just like this
one here, from Pan Am...

33:35.126 --> 33:37.761
the other one is
their FAA license...

33:37.762 --> 33:40.130
and that looks just like this.

33:40.131 --> 33:42.265
Oh. Sir, do you
think I can

33:42.266 --> 33:45.736
make a copy of this
to put into my article?

33:45.737 --> 33:47.538
Oh, Frank, you can
have that one.

33:47.539 --> 33:48.939
It's three years expired.

33:48.940 --> 33:50.541
Aw, thanks!
And what about your I.D. badge?

33:50.542 --> 33:52.075
You have an extra
one I could borrow?

33:52.076 --> 33:54.077
Oh, no, I can't help you there.

33:54.078 --> 33:56.046
Those are special-ordered
from Polaroid.

33:56.047 --> 33:57.548
The only way
to get one of those

33:57.549 --> 34:00.217
is to become a real live pilot
for Pan American Airways.

34:04.990 --> 34:06.624
Pan Am, may I help you?

34:06.625 --> 34:08.091
Yeah, hello.

34:08.092 --> 34:09.159
I'm calling about a uniform.

34:09.159 --> 34:10.928
Hold for Purchasing.

34:10.929 --> 34:11.929
Thank you.

34:11.929 --> 34:13.295
Purchasing.

34:13.297 --> 34:15.297
Hi. I'm a copilot

34:15.299 --> 34:16.600
based out of San Francisco.

34:16.601 --> 34:18.502
I flew a flight
into New York last night

34:18.503 --> 34:19.536
but the problem is

34:19.538 --> 34:21.170
I'm headed out to, uh, Paris
in three hours.

34:21.172 --> 34:23.040
How can we help you?

34:23.041 --> 34:26.109
I sent my uniform to be cleaned
through the hotel

34:26.110 --> 34:28.646
and I... I guess
they must have lost it.

34:28.647 --> 34:31.181
<i>They lost a uniform.
Happens all the time.</i>

34:31.181 --> 34:33.216
<i>Go down to the Well-Built</i>
<i>Uniform Company</i>

34:33.217 --> 34:34.317
<i>at Ninth and Broadway.</i>

34:34.318 --> 34:35.786
<i>They're our uniform supplier.</i>

34:35.786 --> 34:37.487
<i>I'll tell Mr. Rosen</i>
<i>you're coming.</i>

34:37.487 --> 34:39.723
You look too
young to be a pilot.

34:39.724 --> 34:41.491
I'm a copilot.

34:41.492 --> 34:43.159
Why so nervous?

34:43.161 --> 34:44.995
How would you feel if you, uh

34:44.996 --> 34:47.598
lost your uniform
first week on the job?

34:47.599 --> 34:49.232
Relax.

34:49.233 --> 34:51.802
Pan Am's got lots of uniforms.

34:51.803 --> 34:54.103
It's gonna be $164.

34:54.105 --> 34:56.440
Great. I'll, uh,
I'll write you a check.

34:56.440 --> 34:58.542
Sorry, no checks, no cash.

34:58.543 --> 35:00.711
You'll have to fill in
your employee I.D. number

35:00.712 --> 35:01.845
and then I'll bill Pan Am.

35:01.846 --> 35:03.981
They'll take it out
of your next paycheck.

35:05.951 --> 35:07.851
Even better.

35:09.621 --> 35:11.622
<i>Dear Dad,</i>

35:11.623 --> 35:14.558
<i>You always told me that an</i>
<i>honest man has nothing to fear.</i>

35:14.559 --> 35:16.594
<i>So I'm trying my best</i>
<i>not to be afraid.</i>

35:16.595 --> 35:21.131
<i>I'm sorry I ran away,</i>
<i>but you don't have to worry.</i>

35:21.132 --> 35:23.266
<i>I'm gonna get it all back</i>
<i>now, Daddy.</i>

35:23.267 --> 35:25.636
<i>I promise.</i>
<i>I'm going to get it all back.</i>

35:31.375 --> 35:33.443
Are you a real live pilot?

35:33.444 --> 35:35.613
I sure am, little lady.
What's your name?

35:35.614 --> 35:36.614
Celine.

35:36.615 --> 35:38.548
Celine, it's a
pleasure to meet you.

35:38.549 --> 35:40.818
It's a pleasure
to meet you, too.

35:44.222 --> 35:47.024
That's fifty, seventy

35:47.025 --> 35:50.961
eighty, ninety,
one hundred dollars.

35:50.962 --> 35:52.896
You have yourself a
great time in Paris.

35:52.897 --> 35:54.531
I always do.

35:54.532 --> 35:57.518
Excuse me.

35:57.519 --> 35:59.220
I'm John Modiger.
I manage this branch.

35:59.221 --> 36:00.654
I want to thank you
for coming in

36:00.655 --> 36:01.788
and using our institution.

36:01.789 --> 36:03.557
Well, it's a pleasure
to meet you, John.

36:03.558 --> 36:04.558
I'll be back again.

36:04.559 --> 36:05.826
Good.

36:05.827 --> 36:07.461
Have you stayed with us before?

36:07.462 --> 36:10.831
Uh, no, I've been primarily
based on the West Coast.

36:10.832 --> 36:14.235
Is it all right if I write
you a check for the room?

36:14.236 --> 36:15.336
No problem, sir.

36:15.337 --> 36:17.538
Great.

36:24.796 --> 36:25.846
Uh...

36:25.847 --> 36:26.914
I was also wondering

36:26.915 --> 36:28.815
if I could write you
a personal check?

36:28.816 --> 36:32.319
For airline personnel, we cash
personal checks up to $100.

36:32.320 --> 36:34.521
Payroll checks
we cash up to $300.

36:35.723 --> 36:38.526
Did you say $300
for a payroll check?

36:43.131 --> 36:45.533
<i>Dear Dad,</i>

36:45.534 --> 36:48.135
<i>I've decided to become a pilot</i>
<i>for Pan American Airways...</i>

36:48.136 --> 36:51.572
<i>the most trusted name</i>
<i>in the skies.</i>

36:51.573 --> 36:54.275
<i>They've accepted me</i>
<i>into their training program</i>

36:54.276 --> 36:56.277
<i>and told me that if I work hard.</i>

36:56.278 --> 36:57.711
<i>I should earn my wings</i>
<i>real soon.</i>

36:57.712 --> 37:00.414
<i>Please get in touch with Joanna</i>
<i>Carlton from the tenth grade.</i>

37:00.415 --> 37:03.817
<i>Tell her I'm sorry that I could</i>
<i>not take her to the Junior Prom.</i>

37:03.818 --> 37:06.019
<i>Love, your son, Frank.</i>

37:44.692 --> 37:45.826
Hello, how are you?

37:45.827 --> 37:46.994
Fine, thank you.

37:46.995 --> 37:48.996
I have a payroll check here
I'd like to cash.

37:48.997 --> 37:50.664
Certainly.

37:50.665 --> 37:51.865
Thank you.

37:53.418 --> 37:54.768
Uh, excuse me.

37:54.769 --> 37:56.703
I'm sure you hear this
all the time

37:56.704 --> 37:59.206
but you have the most
beautiful eyes I have ever seen.

38:00.742 --> 38:02.276
